<h2>Solar Panels in Michigan</h2>
<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Michigan's solar resource is significantly better than many residents realize, with the state receiving between 3.5 to 4.5 peak sun hours daily depending on location. Southern Michigan, including cities like Ann Arbor, Grand Rapids, and Kalamazoo, experiences the highest solar irradiance levels, while northern regions still maintain viable solar potential. The state's relatively cool temperatures actually benefit solar panel efficiency, as photovoltaic systems operate more effectively in cooler conditions compared to extremely hot climates.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Michigan can produce between 1,100 to 1,400 kWh per year per installed kilowatt, depending on system orientation, tilt angle, and local weather patterns. South-facing roofs with minimal shading provide optimal production, though east and west-facing installations can still achieve 80-85% of south-facing efficiency. Michigan's snowy winters don't significantly impact annual production, as snow typically slides off tilted panels and the reflective properties of snow can actually boost production on clear winter days.</p>

<p>The state's net metering policies allow homeowners to receive retail credit for excess solar production, making it possible to offset winter energy consumption with summer surplus generation. This seasonal balance is particularly important in Michigan, where heating loads in winter can be substantial, but summer solar production peaks. Advanced monitoring systems help homeowners track their production and consumption patterns, optimizing their energy usage to maximize savings throughout the year.</p>

