<h2>Michigan Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Michigan homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the full cost of the solar system, including equipment, installation, and electrical work, making it one of the most valuable incentives available.</p>

<p>The state of Michigan offers a property tax exemption for solar installations, meaning that while your solar system adds value to your home, it won't increase your property tax burden. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the life of the system. Additionally, Michigan has no state sales tax on solar equipment, further reducing the upfront cost of installation. The state's net metering law requires utilities to credit customers at retail rates for excess solar production, maximizing the value of every kilowatt-hour generated.</p>

<p>DTE Energy and Consumers Energy offer various rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC equipment. DTE's Energy Efficiency program provides rebates up to \$300 for high-efficiency air conditioners, \$400 for heat pumps, and \$600 for smart thermostats when installed with qualifying equipment. Consumers Energy offers similar rebates, including up to \$500 for geothermal heat pump installations and \$200 for programmable thermostats. Many local municipalities also offer additional incentives, and low-interest financing programs through Michigan Saves make it easier for homeowners to invest in energy-efficient upgrades without significant upfront costs.</p>

